---

# 3. 🔄 Token Flow Model (How PNJC moves in the system)

## 3.1 Primary Flow (Lifecycle of PNJC)

[
\text{Mint/Allocation} \rightarrow \text{Vesting Lock} \rightarrow \text{Staking / Circulation} \rightarrow \text{DEX Liquidity}
]

### Step-by-step:

### 1. Allocation Phase

* Tokens are assigned to:

  * team
  * liquidity
  * staking rewards
  * airdrops

---

### 2. Vesting Phase

* Allocated tokens enter **time-locked vesting contracts**
* No transfer possible before cliff

---

### 3. Unlock Phase

* Tokens are gradually released:

[
V_i(t) \rightarrow C(t)
]

* unlocked tokens become part of circulating supply

---

### 4. Circulation Phase

* Tokens enter:

  * staking pools
  * liquidity pools
  * user wallets

---

### 5. Market Phase

* Tokens interact with DEX liquidity pools:

  * Uniswap / Quickswap trading
  * price discovery mechanism

---

# 4. 🧠 Staking ↔ Vesting Relationship Model

## 4.1 System Interaction Logic

Staking and vesting are **mathematically linked but functionally separated**.

---

### 🔗 Relationship Equation:

[
S_{effective}(t) = S_{vested}(t) - S_{staked}(t)
]

Where:

* ( S_{vested}(t) ) = unlocked tokens from vesting
* ( S_{staked}(t) ) = tokens locked in staking contracts

---

## 4.2 Economic Behavior Model

### Vesting increases supply:

[
\frac{dC(t)}{dt} > 0
]

### Staking decreases circulating pressure:

[
C_{effective}(t) = C(t) - S_{staked}(t)
]

---

## 4.3 System Effect

| Mechanism       | Effect               |
| --------------- | -------------------- |
| Vesting unlock  | ↑ circulating supply |
| Staking lock    | ↓ circulating supply |
| Combined system | supply stabilization |

---

## 4.4 Key Insight

> Vesting introduces controlled inflation pressure
> Staking absorbs inflation by locking supply

---

# 5. 💧 Router ↔ Liquidity Interaction Model

## 5.1 Liquidity System Architecture

```
User → PNJC_Free_Router → Liquidity Pool (DEX)
```

---

## 5.2 Router Function Role

The router acts as a **controlled execution layer between users and liquidity pools**.

### Functions:

* swap execution
* route validation
* slippage control
* liquidity pool selection

---

## 5.3 Liquidity Impact Model

### Liquidity State:

[
L(t) = L_{in} - L_{out}
]

Where:

* ( L_{in} ) = liquidity added to pool
* ( L_{out} ) = liquidity removed via trades

---

### Router influence:

[
\Delta L(t) = f(\text{swap volume}, \text{slippage}, \text{MEV pressure})
]

---

## 5.4 Market Impact Equation

[
P(t) \propto \frac{Demand(t)}{Liquidity(t)}
]

Where router directly affects:

* execution efficiency
* slippage stability
* price impact depth

---

# 6. 🔐 Governance Flow (Multisig Control Layer)

```
Proposal → Multisig Approval → Execution → Contract State Change
```

### Controlled actions:

* router updates
* emergency pause
* treasury allocation
* parameter adjustments

---

# 7. 🧾 System State Machine

## 7.1 Global Protocol States:

| State              | Description              |
| ------------------ | ------------------------ |
| Initialization     | contracts deployed       |
| Vesting Active     | locked allocations       |
| Circulation Active | tokens unlocked          |
| Staking Active     | yield generation enabled |
| Market Active      | DEX trading enabled      |

---

## 7.2 Transition Logic:

[
S_n \rightarrow S_{n+1} \quad \text{only via multisig or time conditions}
]

---

# 8. 📊 Security Separation Model

| Layer      | Risk Isolation       |
| ---------- | -------------------- |
| Token      | immutable core       |
| Vesting    | time-bound locks     |
| Staking    | reward isolation     |
| Router     | controlled execution |
| Governance | multisig constraint  |

---

# 9. 🧠 Key System Properties

✔ Deterministic token flow
✔ No hidden mint pathways
✔ Separation of liquidity and governance
✔ Time-locked supply release
✔ Staking-based supply absorption
✔ Router-controlled market interaction

---

# 10. 🧮 Formal System Representation

The entire protocol can be defined as:

[
\mathcal{P} =
(T, V, S, R, G)
]

Where:

* ( T ) = Token layer
* ( V ) = Vesting system
* ( S ) = Staking system
* ( R ) = Router + liquidity system
* ( G ) = Governance (multisig)

---

# 🏁 Final Statement

> The PanjoCoin architecture is designed as a modular DeFi system where token emission, liquidity formation, and governance execution are strictly separated to minimize systemic risk and ensure deterministic token behavior.

